# data-counter.note

A 4-second counter-up animation: a single big number tweens from 0 → target, with a
short caption label below it. Useful as a beat inside a longer explainer, or as a
standalone "metric reveal" card.

---

**Target duration:** 4 s
**Aspect:** 16:9
**Camera hint:** none — purely typographic, no parallax

**Scene prompt (paste into Generate panel)**:

> Large numeric counter at center that tweens from 0 to TARGET using
> `interpolate(frame, [0, 90], [0, TARGET], { extrapolateRight: 'clamp' })`.
> Below the number, a small caption label fades in by frame 30 and stays until
> frame 120. Background is a flat dark slate. Number formatted with thousand
> separators. Use a tabular-nums style so the digits do not jitter as they grow.

**Replace these tokens before generating**:

| Token | Example |
|---|---|
| TARGET | `12500` |
| Caption label | `events processed last hour` |

**References**:

- monospaced or tabular-figure font for the counter (no width-shifting digits)
- counter occupies ~60% of vertical height
- caption is one short line, never wraps

**Why this clip works as a template**

- One `interpolate()` call drives the whole composition — the simplest possible
  agent-generated motion. If a refactor breaks animation handling, this is the
  first thing to fail.
- 16:9 + tabular nums + caption is also the canonical "metric beat" shape used
  in many longer explainers; you can drop the output into a bigger clip later.
